article.description: Epiphanny Prince scored 25 points and Kia Vaughn had 10 points and eight assists to help Rutgers (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) snap a two-game losing streak and rally past Temple 64-60 on Monday night.
article.headline: Prince scores 19 in second half to help No. 11 Rutgers avoid third straight loss
article.linkText: Second-half rally helps No. 11 Rutgers end skid
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA -- Even an unranked team gave Rutgers (No. 11 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) fits.

Down by 15 points in the first half, the Scarlet Knights were on the brink of their longest losing streak in five years. Unlike a futile effort on the West Coast, however, Rutgers was good enough to rally on the road and win.

Epiphanny Prince scored 25 points and Kia Vaughn had 10 points and eight rebounds to help Rutgers snap a two-game skid by rallying past Temple 64-60 on Monday night.

"We were lucky to win the game," Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer said.

The Scarlet Knights (3-2) had to hang on to do it. They turned that double-digit deficit into a seven-point lead late in the game before Lindsay Kimmel hit a pair of 3-pointers in the final minute for the Owls (3-2) that made it a two-point game.

Prince, though, sank the final two free throws of Rutgers' 22-for-24 effort from the line to seal the win. She scored 19 points in the second half and the Scarlet Knights were able to put the disappointment of consecutive losses to No. 3 California and Stanford (No. 6, No. 4) behind them.

"It's obvious we're struggling," Stringer said. "It's going to be some time before we're anywhere near right."

Both of Temple's losses have come to Top 25 teams. Shanea Cotton led the Owls with 18 points and Shenita Landry had 12 points and nine rebounds.

"A victory would have been the best," first-year Temple coach Tonya Cardoza said.

The Owls made Rutgers work hard for the win. They never trailed in the first half and led by as many as 15 before settling for a 32-21 halftime lead. The Owls worked the ball inside early to Cotton and she scored 11 points on 5-for-7 shooting.

The Owls hit consecutive 3s at the start of their run to stretch their lead to double digits for the first time, only to get greedy and keep shooting from long distance.

They fizzled the rest of the game until Kimmel hit her two late 3s. Temple finished a woeful 5-for-27 from beyond the arc.

"We just got 3-point happy," Cardoza said. "We started chucking up too many 3s. We should never shoot 27 3s in a game."

Once Temple abandoned the inside game, the Scarlet Knights got going.

Rutgers went on a 12-2 run to slice the deficit to single digits and took its first lead, 43-42, at the halfway mark of the second.

"I just think we weren't as aggressive in the beginning of the second half as we were in the first half," Cotton said.

Myia McCurdy made two free throws for a 47-45 lead with 8:03 left and Rutgers never trailed again. Prince nailed a couple of jumpers that gave Rutgers some needed momentum in the final minutes.

"They always seem to get hot, especially Epiphanny Prince," Cardoza said.

Rutgers has won 16 of the last 21 meetings with Temple.

Stringer ran a grueling week of practice even after the travel and two tough losses. She hoped the Scarlet Knights got the message that they simply can't bluff their way through games and come away with wins simply because of their tradition. They have to be embarrassed to lose, take it personally and vow to improve like some of the great Rutgers teams of this decade.

"The losses to Cal and Stanford are fine, as long as we learn from it," Stringer said.
